english:
  title: Sometimes Clearing, Sometimes Raining
  author: Kim Si-seup
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Now it clears, then rain returns; rain falls, then clear skies come again.
    Heaven's way is thus—how much more the ways of men's hearts?

    They praise me, and soon enough they tear me down.
    I flee from fame, yet find myself pursuing it.

    Flowers bloom and flowers fade—can spring command their course?
    Clouds depart and clouds return—the mountain does not quarrel.

    I tell the people of this world: remember well—
    There is no place in all your days to find lasting joy.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Kim Si-seup (1435-1493) was a poet, writer, and Buddhist monk of the Joseon dynasty, known for his philosophical and often melancholic reflections on human nature and the impermanence of worldly pursuits.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem employs natural phenomena—changing weather, blooming flowers, drifting clouds—as metaphors for the transience of human reputation and desire, a common theme in East Asian Buddhist-influenced poetry.
